REPLACE INTO multilingual(`key`,language,value,guid) values("abstract","en","A novel species, Salvia akiensis A.Takano, Sera & Kurosaki, from western Honshu, Japan, is described. Salvia akiensis occurs in Hiroshima and Shimane prefectures and flowers in May and June. Salvia akiensis is similar to S. isensis, S. lutescens sensu lato and S. omerocalyx in having long exerted stamens. However, the species can be distinguished from S. isensis by having much larger flowers, and from S. omerocalyx by having one pair of cauline leaves, long pilose hairs on the inside upper half of the calyx tube, multicellular hairs 1-2 mm long on the outside of the dorsal calyx lobe, and pale bluish-purple corollas. It can be distinguished from S. lutescens sensu lato by its smaller flowering shoots, the leaf apex roundish, flowering shoot with a single pair of cauline leaves and larger calyx and corolla.","http://ci.nii.ac.jp/naid/110009832038");
